@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Main part"
@prev "Copyright"

 @{b}Installation through the AT Installer@{ub}

 Open the Install drawer and click on the English icon. Then follow the
 instructions.


 @{b}Manual Installation@{ub}

 If you do not have the AT Installer or simply do not want to use it, you can proceed as
 follows :

 - Copy Xit wherever you want
 - If you wish a default icon :
   . copy the def_xit icon wherever desired,
   . change the Tooltype DEFICON according to the place where you copied
     the def_xit icon.
 - Copy the doc files wherever you want.
 - There is an icon package in the Icon drawer. If you wish to change the AppIcon,
   do it in the tooltypes (APPICON). Do not forget NOT to add the .info extension
   (this is doen automatically).
@endnode

@node "Main Part" "Main Part"
@next "ToolTypes"
@prev "Installation"

 @{b}Main part@{ub}

 The use of Xit is easy. To pack one or several files, just drop their
 icon on the Xit Appicon or Appwindow.

 The drawers can also be dropped and their content will be packed.
 If a sub-drawer is inside a dropped drawer, its content won't be packed.
 The icons won't be packed either.

 You can choose the compression library with the listview, on the left of
 the interface.

 When a library is chosen, its description automatically appears. You can
 see the following information :

  . @{b}Description@{ub}
  . @{b}Efficiency@{ub}
  . @{b}Name of the compression mode@{ub} (according to the chosen efficiency)
  . @{b}(Un)packing speed@{ub}
  . @{b}Compression ratio@{ub}

 This information is very helpful to adapt the compression library to the kind
 of file you want to pack.

 If the input of a password is required or at least possible, the @{b}'Enter Password'@{ub}
 option will be activated.

 You can choose to @{b}'Keep original'@{ub}, i.e. Xit will create a new file with an
 '.xpk' suffix and the sourcefile is not replaced. Either the sourcefile is packed.

 If a @{b}destination@{ub} is chosen, then all packed files will be copied to this
 destination.

 @{b}@{u}The buttons@{ub}@{uu}:
 . @{b}Save@{ub}  : saves the used configuration, i.e. the chosen packing library,
   the efficiency, the compression ratio etc...
 . @{b}Hide@{ub}  : Iconifies the program
 . @{b}Quit@{ub}  : I can't remember... ;-)

 @{b}@{u}Menus@{ub}@{uu}:
  * @{b}Projects@{ub}:
    . @{b}Hide@{ub}               : same function as the 'hide' button
    . @{b}About...@{ub}           : opens the Xit information window
    . @{b}About MUI...@{ub}       : opens the MUI information window
    . @{b}Quit@{ub}               : don't ask !!  8-)
  * @{b}Settings@{ub}:
    . @{b}Save@{ub}               : same function as the 'Save' button
    .@{b} MUI settings@{ub}       : opens the MUI settings window

 That's it. I don't think I can do it easier ;-) ...
@endnode

@node "ToolTypes" "ToolTypes"
@next "Future"
@prev "Main part"

 @{b}ToolTypes@{ub}


 @{b}PROGRESSBAR@{ub}

 Exemple: PROGRESSBAR or (PROGRESSBAR)

 If this tooltype is activated, then a window showing the (un)packing will
 pop up.


 @{b}FLASH@{ub}

 Exemple: FLASH or (FLASH)

 If this tooltype is activated, then the (un)packing will provoke a flash.


 @{b}DEFICON@{ub}

 Exemple: DEFICON=PROGDIR:def_Xit.info

 This tooltype lets you (de)activate the possibility to create a default icon
 for the handled files which haven't one. It also describes the path for the
 default icon.


 @{b}APPICON@{ub}

 Exemple: APPICON=PROGDIR:Xit

 This tooltype chooses the icon that must be used when the program is iconified.
 !!! BEWARE !!! The '.info' suffix will be automatically added.

@endnode

@node "Future" "Future"
@next "Author"
@prev "ToolTypes"

 @{b}What is planned for Xit@{ub}

 Some options I'll probably add to future versions :

 - Automatic recognition of the file type, and packing with an adapted
   XPK library.
 - Possibility to test 3 different packing libraries and use the best.
 - Some more information about the gain:
      Source: 12854546 bytes
      Destination: 14455785 bytes
      Gain: 13%
 - When iconifying Xit, having the name of the XPK library rather than the
   program name.

 ...
@endnode

